d":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tate","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern):","from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Tate</i> (Old English <i>Tāta</i>, from <i>tāt</i> ‘happy’).","usually a variant of   Tait  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tates","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tate  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now very rare in Britain. In the US, it is found mainly among African Americans."]},{"name":"Tade","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of English   Tate  .","North German and East Frisian: from a Frisian short form of a personal name composed with the ancient Germanic element <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ (see   Tack  , compare   Thaden  ). This surname is very rare in Germany and is apparently not found in East Frisia.","Japanese (pronounced as two syllables): written 蓼 ‘knotweed’. Not a common surname."]},{"name":"Tait","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: nickname for a cheerful person, from Middle English and Older Scots <i>tait(e)</i> ‘merry, eager, lively’ (Old Norse <i>teitr</i>), also used as a personal name. Compare   Tate  ."]},{"name":"Tasso","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Giancarlo, Gianpaolo, Lorenzo.  German Dieter.","Italian: topographic name for someone who lived near a prominent yew tree, Italian <i>tasso</i> (from Latin <i>taxus</i>, genitive <i>taxi</i>).","Italian: from the personal name <i>Tas(s)o</i>, derived from the obscure ancient Germanic element <i>tāt</i>, possibly akin to Old High German <i>tāt</i> ‘deed’. Compare English   Tate  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Hebrew.  See  <b>Maria</b>   and   <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Mary Agnes Tate Baroness of Chandler was born in 1512, in Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with John Page. She died in 1566, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1512–1566":"1512–1566","1510–1556":"1510–1556","1531–1606":"1531–1606","before 5 May 1556":"enne 5. maid 1556","1512":"1512","1556":"1556","1566":"1566","1510":"1510","1531":"1531","1606":"1606","8 July 1531":"8. juuli 1531","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Hereford, Herefo